nowledge?', 1892, 0), (331229, 'Yet the Narrator’s quest is not only for his own identity and vocation. He seeks an understanding of art, sexuality and worldly and political affairs: he is a snoop and a voyeur; he comments and classifies; his taxonomic impulse makes the novel appear to be a vast compendium, replete with burrowing wasps and bedsteads, military strategies, stereoscopes, asparagus and aeroplanes.', 54438, 0), (331230, 'The select natures who pant after the ideal, and find nothing in pantaloons or petticoats great enough to command their reverence and love, are curiously in unison with the narrowest and pettiest.', 215, 0), (331231, 'Most will regret opening up the doors to truth, while others will cower at thought of living an illusion. In the end, does impracticality defeat curiosity?', 3696, 0), (331232, 'Old timidity has disappeared, and is replaced by silent, quaint fun, with which his face twinkles all over, as he listens.', 33868, 0), (331233, 'I nibbled my lower lip. "If you could see into my past just by touching my back, you''d have a hard time resisting the temptation too.""I have a hard time keeping my hands off you without that added bonus.', 155, 0), (331234, 'If they substituted the word ''Lust'' for ''Love'' in the popular songs it would come nearer the truth.', 140, 0), (331235, '...as long as nothing happens between them, the memory is cursed with what hasn''t happened.', 706, 0), (331236, 'He grinned. “I was trying to remember all the deadly sins the other day,” he said. “Greed,envy, gluttony, irony, pedantry…”“I’m pretty sure irony isn’t a deadly sin.”“I’m pretty sure it is.”“Lust,” she said. “Lust is a deadly sin.”“And spanking.”“I think that falls under lust.”“I think it should have its own category,” said Jace. “Greed, envy, gluttony, irony, pedantry, lust, and spanking.', 39, 0), (331237, 'Well enough,” I reply. “Remember, you’re drunk. And happy. You’re supposed to be lusting over your escort. Try smiling a little mo', 237, 0), 